      <trans-unit id="13790" identifier="cd406a2dc4b87a88cd42e6d14944d349">
        <source>The Modulo operator Unplugged</source>
        <target>crwdns13790:0crwdne13790:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 1&#13;
XPath: /h1</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13791" identifier="7a3e2f2bf06c075a85537ccd137173ae">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;note&quot; title=&quot;Note from the authors&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns13791:0crwdne13791:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13792" identifier="74a1f0857ca1895f3770535e7deb762c">
        <source>This lesson is primarily on a maths topic rather than Computational Thinking,
but the modulo operator is so widely used in digital systems that we've
provided this lesson plan to teach it explicitly rather than introduce it in
each of the several topics that use it.</source>
        <target>crwdns13792:0crwdne13792:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13793" identifier="02e22f39c3deff49a623c2cffcd69ae7">
        <source>The &quot;mod&quot; operation (short for modulo) is used a lot in the error correction
and detection lessons; in the Unplugged activities it also comes up in
searching (hashing), and it applies to angles in turtle based languages like
Scratch and Logo.</source>
        <target>crwdns13793:0crwdne13793:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13794" identifier="ba487e03b86dbd0f5e43b6e53a88b8fd">
        <source>Students may already be familiar with the idea, since it is essentially the
same as the &quot;remainder&quot; after division; it's also referred to as &quot;clock
arithmetic&quot; because it is how we can add time.</source>
        <target>crwdns13794:0crwdne13794:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13795" identifier="3a1ae082a90b504339024ac691a2b919">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns13795:0{panel end}crwdne13795:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13796" identifier="f17e7b5da610295808d4668fae87df1b">
        <source>Key questions</source>
        <target>crwdns13796:0crwdne13796:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13797" identifier="e8538adf8fc4cf62cca52d806a1ce5cf">
        <source>Which month comes first, January or December?
What is the month after December?</source>
        <target>crwdns13797:0crwdne13797:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13798" identifier="617ca5db75a7e764d684d737addfdcc3">
        <source>What is the weekday that comes after Friday?
What is the weekday that is 4 days before Friday?</source>
        <target>crwdns13798:0crwdne13798:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13799" identifier="ac30fdeb886d54cb70874e6f9b9e9109">
        <source>If you arrive at a car park at 5pm (17:00 if you use 24 hour time),
and pay for 8 hours of parking, when will it expire?</source>
        <target>crwdns13799:0crwdne13799:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13800" identifier="99b0f7b08a0fea55d9673bbf7f187851">
        <source>Potential answers could include:</source>
        <target>crwdns13800:0crwdne13800:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13801" identifier="a3e1119f42ea76294132aa32b093f918">
        <source>With the months, each month is both before and after every other month!
If it's January, then there's a December just before it, but there's also
one coming up in 11 months.</source>
        <target>crwdns13801:0crwdne13801:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13802" identifier="3558e525fd4cb1bde26b57aee370a3af">
        <source>With the days, again, Monday comes after Friday, but it's also before
Friday.</source>
        <target>crwdns13802:0crwdne13802:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13803" identifier="2c7ba7abb6c205872653dee50827a8cd">
        <source>The car parking ticket expires at 1am (1:00).
When you add 8 to 5 (or 17), you get 1!</source>
        <target>crwdns13803:0crwdne13803:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13804" identifier="4460fd52c3ef567c91cd109657e20025">
        <source>Lesson starter</source>
        <target>crwdns13804:0crwdne13804:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13805" identifier="cc934edca9fbb607a5cad909fa2d3b69">
        <source>Print the modulo clock resource with modulo 10 out for the students, or draw
it on the board (This sequence of questions could also be run using the train
or ferris wheel model; see the next section).</source>
        <target>crwdns13805:0crwdne13805:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13806" identifier="dcef983078aad62e57515169a47093ff">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/modulo-10-clock.png&quot; alt=&quot;A clock face with the numbers 0 to 9 around inside.&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns13806:0crwdne13806:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13807" identifier="e682a18a34842b481c163c9cc4e95ca0">
        <source>Ask what is unusual about this &quot;clock&quot; (it has only 10 points on the dial,
and it has 0 at the top instead of 10).
Explain that although it's a little odd, it's actually very useful.</source>
        <target>crwdns13807:0crwdne13807:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13808" identifier="ea08f2f76d1ef4a9f87b3ba4c0221b4a">
        <source>Lesson activities</source>
        <target>crwdns13808:0crwdne13808:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13809" identifier="cb4283bdbcfa7d2770556dd86747156f">
        <source>Ask which number is 2 hours (or 2 ticks) after 3?</source>
        <target>crwdns13809:0crwdne13809:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13810" identifier="57a6cb77b2a27f5576667a6dc3961794">
        <source>(The answer is 5 i.e. just count 2 units clockwise).</source>
        <target>crwdns13810:0crwdne13810:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13811" identifier="29b34affa21cdf3f4092f0411166f1c1">
        <source>If students have their own copy of the clock, they could put a counter on
the 3, and move it 2 places.</source>
        <target>crwdns13811:0crwdne13811:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13812" identifier="f7b0569878ceca859734fa9121ac3944">
        <source>Which is 3 hours after 9? (2) We'll refer to this as 9+3.</source>
        <target>crwdns13812:0crwdne13812:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[8]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13813" identifier="a14fccd6b1b7b4e0433d5be86d93f3c1">
        <source>What is 2+10 (i.e. 10 ticks after 2)?</source>
        <target>crwdns13813:0crwdne13813:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13814" identifier="1f70ec9054174c720ce7efcb68cae9b7">
        <source>(It is 2, since adding 10 goes right around the clock).</source>
        <target>crwdns13814:0crwdne13814:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13815" identifier="5522bc9193449715117dbab64ba60125">
        <source>What is 2+20?</source>
        <target>crwdns13815:0crwdne13815:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13816" identifier="988e36284b47f67a496c8afe61098e0e">
        <source>(it's also 2; you go around the clock twice).</source>
        <target>crwdns13816:0crwdne13816:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13817" identifier="52afa69d55b13d186b07576a4c94ecc5">
        <source>What is 5+100?</source>
        <target>crwdns13817:0crwdne13817:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13818" identifier="c4714fef1de4d374c3acbc94b13f95fa">
        <source>(5, since going a multiple of 10 gets you back to the same place).</source>
        <target>crwdns13818:0crwdne13818:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13819" identifier="8ed446b69f2e061dbfcfb62bd060c164">
        <source>Now compare the following sums on the clock with the normal sum:</source>
        <target>crwdns13819:0crwdne13819:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[10]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13820" identifier="eee9d5e025e99bf06bf40da9c7869aae">
        <source>8+3 (1, compared with 11).</source>
        <target>crwdns13820:0crwdne13820:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13821" identifier="e5ed123fa0f0374831bde4fb6fa231b6">
        <source>9+8+7 (4, compared with 24).</source>
        <target>crwdns13821:0crwdne13821:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13822" identifier="3f4e4fce8a9e5c177f9fb904efe0ea28">
        <source>6+6+6 (8, compared with 18).</source>
        <target>crwdns13822:0crwdne13822:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13823" identifier="2e2858a5f658c673c15e994819124164">
        <source>Ask the students if they can see the pattern; with sufficient examples they
will realise that it keeps the last digit of the sum e.g. the last digit of
11 is 1, of 24 is 4, and of 18 is 8.</source>
        <target>crwdns13823:0crwdne13823:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13824" identifier="54609d142cbdc59703485813371bdce3">
        <source>If they have done the product code activity, they may recognise this as the
function that we use for working out the check digit in product codes.</source>
        <target>crwdns13824:0crwdne13824:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13825" identifier="14713bf26c69b9bdeda9e8a75b8d1dc5">
        <source>The last calculation above is 3 times 6 (you could start at 0 and
count 6 ticks 3 times).</source>
        <target>crwdns13825:0crwdne13825:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13826" identifier="67fa5c4c58fe12af7e04e41bb3af8cec">
        <source>Ask what 4 times 6 might be on the clock (it's 4, which is
the last digit of 24).
How about 8 times 5? (it's 0, since it's the same as the number 40).</source>
        <target>crwdns13826:0crwdne13826:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[13]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13827" identifier="3e959b9c7328659c843727d27dd848c0">
        <source>This strange kind of clock arithmetic that we're doing has a name:
it's the &lt;em&gt;modulo&lt;/em&gt;.</source>
        <target>crwdns13827:0crwdne13827:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13828" identifier="d43f6bd46438daa67bb7317696ebec85">
        <source>The clock here has 10 ticks on it, so the correct way to write
a calculation is: &lt;code&gt;(8+3) modulo 10&lt;/code&gt;.</source>
        <target>crwdns13828:0crwdne13828:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13829" identifier="c103b18a301983095c8db77af0d9b976">
        <source>This means add the 8 and 3, but reset to zero every time you would have
got to 10.</source>
        <target>crwdns13829:0crwdne13829:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[15]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13830" identifier="8adb618352ab1d25b8cd70bbbd420147">
        <source>(This function is also called the &quot;remainder&quot; after division, which for
positive numbers is the same as the modulo.)</source>
        <target>crwdns13830:0crwdne13830:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[16]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13831" identifier="bbd2b902152d33426f36892d8ceb6050">
        <source>Ferris wheels and train routes</source>
        <target>crwdns13831:0crwdne13831:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13832" identifier="828a1c7a4a5a702ada2d7db6b1315fa4">
        <source>The above exercise could also be done with the train or ferris wheel handouts,
which also cycle every 10 steps.</source>
        <target>crwdns13832:0crwdne13832:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13833" identifier="4e432da0f85f04d0260147c5c4df348b">
        <source>Students can use counters to track their movement around the stations.</source>
        <target>crwdns13833:0crwdne13833:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13834" identifier="2587fe66aa912613ea2e974627c20191">
        <source>We have provided resources for train routes above.</source>
        <target>crwdns13834:0crwdne13834:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13835" identifier="266b706cd1e7052eccf2c01a804b2c19">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/modulo-train-stations-tracks-circular.png&quot; alt=&quot;A circle of 10 train stations connected by train tracks.&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns13835:0crwdne13835:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13836" identifier="76704f3699dfb6591b1e4c35063997fa">
        <source>Time to rewind</source>
        <target>crwdns13836:0crwdne13836:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13837" identifier="2ad8a5609816a3733072922845b99f62">
        <source>The modulo counting is like a circular number line.</source>
        <target>crwdns13837:0crwdne13837:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13838" identifier="3f39fec4e8f4c18ecc2ad054e4eabe99">
        <source>As well as going forward, let's experiment with going backwards
(i.e. subtraction, or adding negative numbers).</source>
        <target>crwdns13838:0crwdne13838:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13839" identifier="9945e4b25f84903ba83be494b864cac0">
        <source>On the clock it would be winding the time back; on the train and ferris
wheel it's going in reverse.</source>
        <target>crwdns13839:0crwdne13839:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13840" identifier="7220d3bbbdcf9f3c28b58659d41a4a29">
        <source>Ask the class what they think 2 - 4 is on this system (i.e. 4 steps before 2).
(This takes you to location 8).</source>
        <target>crwdns13840:0crwdne13840:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13841" identifier="4d71eb9eaf722a2a1ad46d33ca15d63c">
        <source>How about 2 - 10? (It's still 2).
Or 2-100?
(We're still going to end up at 2).</source>
        <target>crwdns13841:0crwdne13841:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13842" identifier="f954faabe32eda0f8de8f81c88a60eb9">
        <source>What is 0 - 7? (3)</source>
        <target>crwdns13842:0crwdne13842:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[22]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13843" identifier="9812a18b54d3773c85a93c5376da4471">
        <source>But what about -8 i.e. negative 8?
(That's 8 units before 0, which is 4.)
Other numbers that land at 4 are -18, -28, and so on.</source>
        <target>crwdns13843:0crwdne13843:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13844" identifier="43ef36e461518d36161032680490ee12">
        <source>(This idea comes up with calculating some check digits; for several systems
we need to ask &quot;what do you add to x to get to 0 in modulo 10&quot;;
the short way to calculate that in a computer program is &quot;(0-x) mod 10&quot;.)</source>
        <target>crwdns13844:0crwdne13844:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13845" identifier="580c1b293764ba179644dcbbf0b79fe9">
        <source>Other sized clocks</source>
        <target>crwdns13845:0crwdne13845:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13846" identifier="72166750d35af85d12982b2c77135077">
        <source>Now have the students imagine (or draw) a clock with 11 ticks on it,
numbered from 0 to 10.</source>
        <target>crwdns13846:0crwdne13846:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[25]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13847" identifier="526dc6640292f8f64b69540c190455e0">
        <source>What is 9+3 on this clock (it's 1).</source>
        <target>crwdns13847:0crwdne13847:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[26]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13848" identifier="3cbdee37bb8e6efd04ee26efb19e008d">
        <source>What is 7+11? (7, since 11 goes right around the clock).</source>
        <target>crwdns13848:0crwdne13848:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[27]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13849" identifier="77bcd6b27bf66da8c216dcab28e493d4">
        <source>You can experiment with other sums, and other clock sizes.
Modulo 11 is mentioned because it is used by ISBN-10 numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns13849:0crwdne13849:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[28]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13850" identifier="2e9bbd2dfce4d8c7892bb1e0f7af6d80">
        <source>If you get the students to consider modulo 12 or 24, they should see that it
relates to normal clocks (12-hour or 24-hour clocks respectively).</source>
        <target>crwdns13850:0crwdne13850:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[29]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13851" identifier="9caf3290523bb385c2c14ee6d823b8ee">
        <source>For example, (8+5) modulo 12 is the same as working out what the time is 5
hours after 8 o'clock; or (22+4) modulo 24 is the same as working out the
time 4 hours after 22:00.</source>
        <target>crwdns13851:0crwdne13851:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[29]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13852" identifier="377a765ff0a6bb640033698786e124e1">
        <source>In the modulo system, the number at the top of the clock would be 0 rather
than 12 or 24, but all the other values work as expected.</source>
        <target>crwdns13852:0crwdne13852:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[29]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13853" identifier="8c33f77a40d5fceca87f4edef55749e9">
        <source>An interesting one to experiment with is modulo 360 i.e. a clock with 360
ticks, numbered from 0 to 359.</source>
        <target>crwdns13853:0crwdne13853:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[30]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13854" identifier="0e6dd7795de0cbb56a01b8a6268a52b6">
        <source>This kind of calculation happens when we add angles, since turning 360 degrees
ends up in the same place as the starting position.</source>
        <target>crwdns13854:0crwdne13854:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[30]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13855" identifier="07423ed6c0bd7f3f39c2c49b7900a8e9">
        <source>Have the students stand up and face the front.
Now ask them to turn right 90 degrees (a right angle).
Now have them turn another 90 degrees.
Ask what angle they've turned in total (180 degrees).</source>
        <target>crwdns13855:0crwdne13855:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[31]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13856" identifier="d2f4aaaf56c01df23656aac9220b8272">
        <source>Continuing on, have them turn 90 degrees twice more.</source>
        <target>crwdns13856:0crwdne13856:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[32]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13857" identifier="bbdf2200ca20059c672d642960434feb">
        <source>They should now be facing the front.</source>
        <target>crwdns13857:0crwdne13857:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[32]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13858" identifier="63f53f85c90ef40e1d887620c9c013a4">
        <source>How far have they turned in total?</source>
        <target>crwdns13858:0crwdne13858:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[32]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13859" identifier="8c3b4a34008c0178130eaeab6249f487">
        <source>(90+90+90+90 = 360 degrees)
Students may be familiar with the idea that a &quot;360&quot; represents a full rotation!</source>
        <target>crwdns13859:0crwdne13859:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[32]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13860" identifier="66e14ac6dc9ac3ef02bda3135ba09e1f">
        <source>Now ask which way they would be facing if the turned another 360 degrees?
(It would be facing the front again.)
What if they turn 360 degrees 10 times (i.e. 3600 degrees)?
(Still facing the front).</source>
        <target>crwdns13860:0crwdne13860:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[33]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13861" identifier="564e4ffc7c232c2a5e5c4272394306f3">
        <source>Using similar questions, help the students to realise that the total of the
angles they turn modulo 360 gives the final result.</source>
        <target>crwdns13861:0crwdne13861:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[34]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13862" identifier="5a44671d710780eba47fb15460220074">
        <source>For example, turning 3690 degrees to the right is the same as turning 90
degrees to the right (and the latter is a lot easier!)
Doing rotations is just another kind of modulo arithmetic.</source>
        <target>crwdns13862:0crwdne13862:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[34]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13863" identifier="bcdd309391ba1307bfcf728343170868">
        <source>Doing these calculations in modulo 360 relates to programming in turtle-based
languages such as Scratch and Logo, where sprites turn through angles.</source>
        <target>crwdns13863:0crwdne13863:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[35]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13864" identifier="d6c0869986dffe95fde5a0ac36694735">
        <source>Turning left 90 degrees six times is the same as turning 540 degrees,
but that puts the sprite in the same direction as it would be if it had
turned 180 degrees.</source>
        <target>crwdns13864:0crwdne13864:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[35]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13865" identifier="adda7177cfea51382844c89ff643e0fa">
        <source>Likewise, turning 3600 (or 360, or 720) degrees is the same as turning
0 degrees!</source>
        <target>crwdns13865:0crwdne13865:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[35]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13866" identifier="3d241cea18979919e6fe5db64f172d0d">
        <source>And 365 degrees is the same as 5 degrees.</source>
        <target>crwdns13866:0crwdne13866:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[35]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13867" identifier="a01bb2004d524fd251f87f50413db284">
        <source>Turning -10 degrees is the same as 350 degrees.</source>
        <target>crwdns13867:0crwdne13867:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[35]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13868" identifier="8feffc200b661efb2f5328c1f738b4db">
        <source>Going to another extreme, ask the students to consider a clock with only
two marks on it.
What would they be? (They would be 0 and 1).</source>
        <target>crwdns13868:0crwdne13868:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[36]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13869" identifier="8eb9f1590d19fce4b041d1f8bf72c139">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/modulo-2-clock.png&quot; alt=&quot;A clock face with the number 0 at the top (12 o'clock position) and number 1 at the bottom (6 o'clock position).&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns13869:0crwdne13869:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[37]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13870" identifier="b41b525c75773e4010c1eb5d9de51f43">
        <source>In this modulo 2 system, what is 1+1? (0).</source>
        <target>crwdns13870:0crwdne13870:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[38]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13871" identifier="c730b8f02794f742c9d1f6abf54b1091">
        <source>What is 1+1+1? (1).</source>
        <target>crwdns13871:0crwdne13871:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[39]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13872" identifier="b25007144251ff723a05c629a2f6b8c8">
        <source>Count up through the numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns13872:0crwdne13872:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13873" identifier="54091659faee31283a381aa6ed43173d">
        <source>For example, 4 is 4 ticks past 0, which gets you back to 0.</source>
        <target>crwdns13873:0crwdne13873:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13874" identifier="dc7ed5692f63f0795861d3d08f317202">
        <source>Moving 5 ticks gets you to 1, 6 gets you back to 0.</source>
        <target>crwdns13874:0crwdne13874:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13875" identifier="3b30663b9c1bb8eb5f9e18fea93b55c6">
        <source>With some hints, students should realise that a number modulo 2 tells you
if it is odd or even.</source>
        <target>crwdns13875:0crwdne13875:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13876" identifier="34ac7aee866a8b40df94e721c1b8fe56">
        <source>This is used for the parity code!</source>
        <target>crwdns13876:0crwdne13876:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13877" identifier="a17685ff3e2bcd349b0e4a5bfb41af17">
        <source>If you count black as 1 and white as 0, then each line with even
parity adds up to 0 modulo 2.</source>
        <target>crwdns13877:0crwdne13877:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13878" identifier="26b7c0185feaea4fad16b2e6ee6060df">
        <source>There's a parity error if it adds up to 1 modulo 2; and the extra
bit that was added can be thought of as the value needed to make the
line add up to 0, which is the same idea that is used for most of
the other checksums, just with a different modulo!</source>
        <target>crwdns13878:0crwdne13878:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13879" identifier="a134886e826f4a5afd4995e5540f4074">
        <source>Does the order matter?</source>
        <target>crwdns13879:0crwdne13879:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13880" identifier="44326e92190c15a9126412c322effde5">
        <source>Going back to the modulo 10 clock, ask students if the number 7+8 is
different to the number 8+7.</source>
        <target>crwdns13880:0crwdne13880:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[41]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13881" identifier="2efe0a9284296e7d0c788201bc273fbe">
        <source>(They aren't, since they both are 15 ticks after 0).</source>
        <target>crwdns13881:0crwdne13881:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[41]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13882" identifier="eeaa8a66a4dbe5cb7cd3117fc9ea94fc">
        <source>If necessary, use more examples, so that students recognise that this new
way of adding isn't affected by the order.</source>
        <target>crwdns13882:0crwdne13882:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[41]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13883" identifier="1705cce438d52f093f1eeb7c2fce614a">
        <source>Likewise, have them experiment with applying the mod function at each
step of adding three numbers, compared with adding them first.</source>
        <target>crwdns13883:0crwdne13883:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13884" identifier="e48bb15c7962d4c4507ca4a0eb30a6b0">
        <source>For example, 7+8+6 gets to 1 on the clock.</source>
        <target>crwdns13884:0crwdne13884:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13885" identifier="2810a845a14e11a9bb096de6e1743855">
        <source>Now have them consider 7+8 (which gets to 5), and then add the 6 to it.</source>
        <target>crwdns13885:0crwdne13885:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13886" identifier="5b1ac764dbc18b76de94d54321e1a57e">
        <source>It turns out that you can apply the modulo at each step, or just
at the end; both give the same result.</source>
        <target>crwdns13886:0crwdne13886:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13887" identifier="f54c26b97abc23f96456a947d2e6fda3">
        <source>This means that you can add numbers up quickly by grouping them.
For example, suppose you're adding up: 3 + 7 + 2 + 9 + 1 + 3</source>
        <target>crwdns13887:0crwdne13887:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[43]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13888" identifier="7ad1f5756e22cb59cf18084010c8b837">
        <source>You could work out the total (25), which is 5 in modulo 10.
Or you could add up the digits in pairs.
In this example, the first two digits add up to 0 mod 10: 3 + 7 = 0</source>
        <target>crwdns13888:0crwdne13888:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[44]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13889" identifier="5bbb73461eea1cb2ab82306191ea6724">
        <source>This means that the 3 and the 7 cancel each other out - they won't
affect the total.</source>
        <target>crwdns13889:0crwdne13889:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[45]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13890" identifier="de34f23dd8fc9f82cc6e42c0033b74e5">
        <source>There's also a 9+1 in the sum, so that will also make no
difference to the total.</source>
        <target>crwdns13890:0crwdne13890:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[45]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13891" identifier="00d33be0bbe1a5aa5c33f542218153aa">
        <source>That leaves just 2 and 3 to add up, which come to 5 for the grand total.</source>
        <target>crwdns13891:0crwdne13891:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[45]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13892" identifier="265d6f9ba1501670c46dfee3ed3349c4">
        <source>By grouping numbers that add to 10 (or 20 etc.), you can usually add up
several digits quite quickly in your head.</source>
        <target>crwdns13892:0crwdne13892:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[46]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13893" identifier="8bc3ebe479cff0bdb510fc063c27b353">
        <source>This isn't useful on computers, but means you could possibly add up
a product code checksum without even using pencil and paper!</source>
        <target>crwdns13893:0crwdne13893:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[46]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13894" identifier="5e98bbee92f8df039d0f8cbd183c3abe">
        <source>Plugging it in</source>
        <target>crwdns13894:0crwdne13894:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13895" identifier="3f452161b589f98d759448bed9b50348">
        <source>The &quot;modulo&quot; or &quot;mod&quot; function is easily tested in most programming languages.</source>
        <target>crwdns13895:0crwdne13895:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[47]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13896" identifier="a1638f415def0a79e646ccd540c49a56">
        <source>In Scratch, you can just choose the &quot;mod&quot; block from the Operators, type in
two numbers and double click it to see the result:</source>
        <target>crwdns13896:0crwdne13896:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[48]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13897" identifier="269d2d0eb76fc34afb6602bc54b0b597">
        <source>(37)mod(10) // 7

(-3)mod(10) // 7</source>
        <target>crwdns13897:0crwdne13897:0</target>
        <note>Context: Text&#13;
XPath: /pre/code</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13898" identifier="ca062a936d935b8e4ba1572161381f31">
        <source>In several programming languages, the &lt;code&gt;%&lt;/code&gt; sign is used to represent &quot;modulo&quot;,
which is a very confusing choice!</source>
        <target>crwdns13898:0crwdne13898:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[49]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13899" identifier="c417ed3f9838bccae431420d79d908a0">
        <source>You would type &lt;code&gt;37 % 10&lt;/code&gt; to do the above calculation in Python, Java, C, C++,
C#, and JavaScript.</source>
        <target>crwdns13899:0crwdne13899:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[49]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13900" identifier="fa1606725c98198d624714700ea43c0d">
        <source>Some other languages use &lt;code&gt;mod&lt;/code&gt;, including spreadsheets - for example, you
can type &lt;code&gt;=mod(37,10)&lt;/code&gt; in a spreadsheet formula.</source>
        <target>crwdns13900:0crwdne13900:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[49]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13901" identifier="445422c19f4fc94a6696fe045e449fa5">
        <source>You could project a program onto the screen, and ask students to predict
the value when you type in two numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns13901:0crwdne13901:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13902" identifier="d18c9a80cb32169be31ea38c72d92566">
        <source>For example, in Scratch you could put &lt;code&gt;scratch:((8)+(5))mod(12)&lt;/code&gt; into the
Scratch work area and double click it once students make their predictions.</source>
        <target>crwdns13902:0crwdne13902:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13903" identifier="fcb4bce5fc716fa7fc61e6b4db6a2de4">
        <source>In Python you would use &lt;code&gt;(8+5)%12&lt;/code&gt;.</source>
        <target>crwdns13903:0%12crwdne13903:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13904" identifier="e70fa4c9ff86fc82782ffa9069813f81">
        <source>Now try &lt;code&gt;8+4&lt;/code&gt; instead of &lt;code&gt;8+5&lt;/code&gt;.</source>
        <target>crwdns13904:0crwdne13904:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13905" identifier="443a5fb6e6d91e46ae7173a7a88b71c7">
        <source>&lt;code&gt;8+12&lt;/code&gt;?</source>
        <target>crwdns13905:0crwdne13905:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13906" identifier="8e87b96a9b54720bf13a74bfcd2545b8">
        <source>&lt;code&gt;8+24&lt;/code&gt;?</source>
        <target>crwdns13906:0crwdne13906:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13907" identifier="486c590e3b1f238a5645f3b907148167">
        <source>&lt;code&gt;8+25&lt;/code&gt;?</source>
        <target>crwdns13907:0crwdne13907:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13908" identifier="a8bf9c91918a24bcaca2b9db8c3b3946">
        <source>Fun facts</source>
        <target>crwdns13908:0crwdne13908:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13909" identifier="ca59db9a2a5996c1c391bd83b380e129">
        <source>The months of the year are modulo 12; 4 months after November is March,
13 months after January is February, and so on (if you want to use the
modulo function, you'd need to number the months from 0 to 11, which is
a little unconventional).</source>
        <target>crwdns13909:0crwdne13909:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[51]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13910" identifier="73431b6ea4846616cd638526745fa492">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/modulo-keyboard.png&quot; alt=&quot;A keyboard with keys labelled A to G, with the D keys highlighted.&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns13910:0crwdne13910:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[52]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13911" identifier="b168d629e0e595c11da3021bed3b5f94">
        <source>The naming of musical notes is modulo 7; if you start at the note &quot;D&quot; on a
piano, and count up 7 white notes, you'll end up back on &quot;D&quot;,
which is the same note an octave higher.</source>
        <target>crwdns13911:0crwdne13911:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[53]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13912" identifier="2e5824ab55175af5f33ea3261b99b6d4">
        <source>This raises the interesting fact that there are 7 different notes in an octave;
it gets its name because if you count the notes at the start and end
(&quot;D&quot; in this case, there are 8 notes).</source>
        <target>crwdns13912:0crwdne13912:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[53]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13913" identifier="99e8fcda3948758e4014321c3ffa6fd3">
        <source>Actually, there are really 12 different notes in an octave if you count the
black keys (if you go 12 semitones up from the note &quot;D&quot;, you'll end
up at D again), so in this sense the 12 different notes on a piano are a
lot like the 12 months or the 12 ticks on a 12-hour clock;
but it would be really confusing if we referred to the notes
as &quot;January, February,...&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns13913:0crwdne13913:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[54]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13914" identifier="71b57b13739abe9080de4d249e697258">
        <source>The cyclic number relationship comes up when playing notes in computer
programs, which often use a digital representation of piano notes called
MIDI (for example, these numbers are used in Scratch).</source>
        <target>crwdns13914:0crwdne13914:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13915" identifier="9381c180550206d9d0a485f14f152459">
        <source>In this system, middle C is note number 60, C# is 61, and D is 62.</source>
        <target>crwdns13915:0crwdne13915:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13916" identifier="03e358f5f0cbd0f424bcdc2bf06480cb">
        <source>So an octave above 62 is 62+12 = 74.</source>
        <target>crwdns13916:0crwdne13916:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13917" identifier="36d2808541bf2726771d412ea4046029">
        <source>Every 12th number corresponds to the same note name.</source>
        <target>crwdns13917:0crwdne13917:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13918" identifier="9593472b13142bccc3c737e8b73d8611">
        <source>This will be explained in more detail in the activity on programming
musical scales, which is under development.</source>
        <target>crwdns13918:0crwdne13918:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13919" identifier="72bc99e09c55c94a8961dd75f9c13ae2">
        <source>Applying what we have just learnt</source>
        <target>crwdns13919:0crwdne13919:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13920" identifier="4ceea6fa445caee777164bc3b15369b5">
        <source>Mathematical concepts are part of our everyday life.</source>
        <target>crwdns13920:0crwdne13920:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[56]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="13921" identifier="df9b2c3e7d040c13b8c4229b87a08162">
        <source>Modular arithmetic (which uses the modulo function) is the formal term
